docs.lead_paragraph: Ajit Jain, a top lieutenant at Berkshire Hathaway, is on the short list of candidates to succeed Warren E. Buffett, Berkshire's chief executive. Mr. Jain has landed on another, less desirable list: He is a potential witness in the insider-trading trial of Rajat K. Gupta.

headline.main: Insider Jury May Hear A Top Aide At Berkshire

docs.abstract: Berkshire Hathaway executive Ajit Jain, on short list of candidates to succeed Warren E Buffett, is potential witness in the insider trading trial of Rajat K Gupta, charged with leaking corporate information to convicted hedge fund manager Raj Rajaratnam; Jain's role adds to a list of prominent Wall Street and corporate figures who could testify in trial. docs.lead_paragraph: The power of the state can crowd out other forms of community.
docs.abstract: Ross Douthat Op-Ed column argues that new rules requiring religious institutions to provide coverage of contraceptives in their health care plans amounts to telling religious groups that if they do not want to pay for practices they consider immoral, they should only serve their co-religionists and not the wider public; argues that the decision is a threat to any kind of voluntary community that does not share the moral sensitivities of whichever party controls the health care bureaucracy.
